'''Marilyn Jeanne Seely''' (born July 6, 1940)<ref name="Allmusic Bio">{{cite web |last1=Huey |first1=Steve |title=Jeannie Seely: Biography & History |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jeannie-seely-mn0000234004/biography |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> is an American singer, songwriter, record producer, actress and author. Primarily identified with [[country music]], Seely found success with the [[Grammy Award]]-winning song "[[Don't Touch Me]]" (1966). Her [[soul music|soul]]-inspired vocal delivery<ref name="Meadville">{{cite web |title=Big Honor for Jeannie Seely Later This Month |url=https://www.meadvilletribune.com/news/big-honor-for-jeannie-seely-later-this-month/article_33217218-12b4-11ea-9446-8ba8dd6a496c.html |website=[[Meadville Tribune]] |date=2 December 2019 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> gave her the nickname of "Miss Country Soul".<ref name="PBS">{{cite web |last1=Burns |first1=Ken |title=Country Music: Jeannie Seely Biography |url=https://www.pbs.org/kenburns/country-music/jeannie-seely-biography/ |publisher=[[PBS]] |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Seely has been a member of and performer on the [[Grand Ole Opry]], having appeared more times on the program than any other performer (over 5,000 appearances in her 55-year and ongoing tenure).<ref name=honored55years>{{Cite web |last=Windsor |first=Pam |title=Country Singer Jeannie Seely Honored For 55 Years As A Member Of The Grand Ole Opry |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/pamwindsor/2022/09/19/country-singer-jeannie-seely-honored-for-55-years-as-a-member-of-the-grand-ole-opry/ |access-date=2022-09-27 |website=Forbes |language=en}}</ref>

Born and raised in northwestern Pennsylvania, Seely had an early interest in country music, regularly appearing on local radio and television stations. After high school she began a career in the baking industry and moved to California. Switching careers, she began writing songs which would be recorded by other artists. After being briefly signed with [[Challenge Records (1950s-60s label)|Challenge Records]], she moved to [[Nashville, Tennessee]], to further elevate her country music recording career. In Nashville, Seely's "Don't Touch Me" was released on [[Monument Records]] and reached the US country top five. She followed it with several more top ten and 20 songs, including "[[A Wanderin' Man]]" (1967) and "[[I'll Love You More (Than You'll Need)]]" (1968).

Seely then formed a duet musical partnership with [[Jack Greene]] and they began collaborating together in the late 1960s. Their highest-charting single was 1969's "[[Wish I Didn't Have to Miss You]]" and they subsequently toured over the next decade. Her solo career continued with the popular singles "[[Can I Sleep in Your Arms]]" (1973) and "[[Lucky Ladies]]" (1974). After a car accident in 1977, Seely's career went on a brief hiatus and then resumed new projects. This included appeares in the [[Willie Nelson]] film ''[[Honeysuckle Rose (film)|Honeysuckle Rose]]'' and acted in several stage plays, opening a Nashville bar and becoming the first female to host the Grand Ole Opry.

In the 1990s, Seely returned to recording albums with a 1990 eponymous release, followed by her first album of [[Christmas music|holiday music]] in 1994 called ''[[Number One Christmas]]''. Other releases included the critically-acclaimed 2003 release ''[[Life's Highway (Jeannie Seely album)|Life's Highway]]''. Her most recent studio release was 2020's ''[[An American Classic]]'', issued on [[Curb Records]]. Seely has since continued to work the Grand Ole Opry and became a regular host of a weekly radio program on [[Sirius XM]]'s [[Willie's Roadhouse]] broadcast.

==Early life==
Marilyn Jeanne Seely was born in [[Titusville, Pennsylvania]], but raised on a farm near [[Townville, Pennsylvania]].<ref name="Meadville"/> Seely was the youngest of four children born to Irene and Leo Seely. Her father was a farmer and worked at the Titusville Steel Mill. On weekends, he worked [[square dance]]s and played the [[banjo]]. Her mother was a homemaker, but enjoyed singing around the house. Her family and friends often got together to pick and play music in Seely's childhood.{{sfn|Seely|Harman|2002|p=1}} They also listened to weekly [[Grand Ole Opry]] radio broadcasts during Seely's childhood.<ref name="People">{{cite magazine |last1=Kruh |first1=Nancy |title=She's an Opry Record-Setter: Jeannie Seely Celebrates Over 5,000 Performances on Country's Most Famous Stage |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=September 30, 2022 |url=https://people.com/country/jeannie-seely-holds-grand-ole-opry-performance-record/ |access-date=24 July 2024}}</ref>

At age 11, Seely started performing on [[WMGW]]'s local radio show in [[Meadville, Pennsylvania]]<ref name="Meadville"/> and began performing on a local television show in [[Erie, Pennsylvania]].{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=301}} Seely attended Townville High School where she was a [[Cheerleading|cheerleader]] and an [[honors student]].{{sfn|Seely|Harman|2002|p=2}} In high school, Seely was teased for singing country music and being poor.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oerman|2003|p=301}} Following her 1958 high school graduation, she worked as a [[stenographer]] (and later a secretary) at the Titusville Trust Company.{{sfn|Seely|Harman|2002|p=2}} She also took night courses at the American Banking Institute. During this time, Seely was driving during an [[Easter]] winter storm when her car got stuck in the snow. This inspired her to move to southern California where the climate was warmer.<ref name="Meadville 2">{{cite news |last1=Shanley Special |first1=Jean |title=Vision 2022: Untold Story: Jeannie Seely's journey to the Grand Ole Opry |url=https://www.meadvilletribune.com/vision/vision-2022-untold-story-jeannie-seelys-journey-to-the-grand-ole-opry/article_feccc654-89d3-11ec-8292-2758b10a25b3.html |access-date=24 July 2024 |work=[[The Meadville Tribune]] |date=February 21, 2022}}</ref> In 1961, Seely left for California in her [[MG MGA|MGA Roadster convertible]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Harman |first1=Ron |title=Crawford County Native Seely Celebrates 50th Anniversary as Grand Ole Opry Member |url=https://www.meadvilletribune.com/news/crawford-county-native-seely-celebrates-50th-anniversary-as-grand-ole-opry-member/article_9249aeb0-9a5a-11e7-b1e0-3fc30f51ca46.html |website=[[Meadville Tribune]] |date=16 September 2017 |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> She then briefly held a job at a bank in [[Beverly Hills, California]] but realized she wanted to get more involved in the music business, prompting her to obtain a secretarial position at [[Imperial Records]] for half the pay.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=301}} Seely also appeared on a local California television program titled ''Hollywood Jamboree''.<ref name="PBS"/>

==Career==
===1964â€“1965: Early songwriting, first record label and Nashville===
While working as an Imperial Records secretary, Seely started writing songs for [[Four Star Records|Four Star Music]] in California.<ref name="PBS"/> One of the first compositions she wrote was "[[Anyone Who Knows What Love Is (Will Understand)]]". Accompanying herself on piano, she tracked down writer [[Randy Newman]] to help finish the song.<ref name="Anyone">{{cite magazine |last1=Bronson |first1=Fred |title='Anyone Who Knows What Love Is': Why An Obscure '60s Song Is Bigger Than Ever In 2018 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8470437/anyone-who-knows-what-love-is-black-mirror |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=15 August 2018 |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> It would be picked up by [[rhythm and blues music|R&B]] singer [[Irma Thomas]] whose version made the US pop charts in 1964.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Irma Thomas: Billboard chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/irma-thomas/chart-history |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> This was followed by the song "Senses" (co-written with [[Glen Campbell]]), which [[Connie Smith]] cut for her 1965 album ''[[Cute 'n' Country]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=Connie |title=''Cute 'n' Country'' (LP Liner Notes and Album Information) |journal=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor Records]] |date=October 1965 |id=LSP-3444}}</ref> The same year, [[Dottie West]] cut "It Just Takes Practice" (co-written with Gail Talley) for her album ''[[Dottie West Sings]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=West |first1=Dottie |title=''Dottie West Sings'' (Album Notes and Liner Notes) |journal=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]] |date=December 1965 |id=LSP-3490}}</ref> [[Norma Jean (singer)|Norma Jean]] later recorded "Then Go Home to Her" (credited with [[Hank Cochran]]) for her 1966 album ''Please Don't Hurt Me''.<ref>{{cite journal |title=''Please Don't Hurt Me'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]] |date=1966 |id=LPM-3541 (LP Mono)}}</ref>

Seely's songwriting led to her signing a recording contract with the California-based [[Challenge Records (1950s-60s label)|Challenge Records]].<ref name="Crawford">{{cite web |last1=Harman |first1=Ron |title=Decades later, Jeannie Seely returns to Crawford fair |url=https://www.goerie.com/entertainment/20150820/decades-later-jeannie-seely-returns-to-crawford-fair |website=[[GoErie.com]] |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> Her first recording sessions were held in 1964 at [[RCA Studio B]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref name="People"/> From the sessions came three singles: "If I Can't Have You" (1964),<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title="If I Can't Have You"/"Old Memories Never Die" (7" vinyl single) |journal=[[Challenge Records (1950s-60s label)|Challenge Records]] |date=December 1964 |id=59274}}</ref> "A World Without You" (1965)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title="A World Without You"/"Bring It on Back" (7" vinyl single) |journal=[[Challenge Records (1950s-60s label)|Challenge Records]] |date=June 1965 |id=59298 }}</ref> and "Today Is Not the Day" (1965).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title="Today Is Not the Day"/"What Am I Doing in Your World" (7" vinyl single) |journal=[[Challenge Records (1950s-60s label)|Challenge Records]] |date=August 1965 |id=59274}}</ref> According to her website, Seely embarked on a [[West Coast of the United States|US west coast]] tour to promote the singles, leading to her meeting songwriter Hank Cochran.{{sfn|Harman|Seely|2002|p=2}} Impressed by her singing, Cochran encouraged her to move to Nashville to further pursue a country career.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oerman|2003|p=301}} Dottie West (who had developed a friendship with Seely) also encouraged a Nashville move and in 1965, Seely officially left California.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Partridge |first1=Tamela Meredith |title=Jeannie Seely and David Frizzell co-headline at Nashville North |url=https://herald-review.com/entertainment/jeannie-seely-and-david-frizzell-co-headline-at-nashville-north/article_212d5efd-6874-571e-85b8-f359989fd882.html |website=[[Herald & Review]] |date=28 September 2006 |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> She then arrived at the 1965 DJ Convention in Nashville where she saw Cochran again. Cochran then agreed to help Seely with her career, only if he was allowed to have control of her decisions.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=301}} She was then hired as Norma Jean's replacement on [[Porter Wagoner]]'s television series during the same period.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Darrow |first1=Ryan |title=Porter Wagoner Show, The |url=https://tennesseeencyclopedia.net/entries/the-porter-wagoner-show/ |website=Tennessee Encyclopedia |access-date=25 July 2024}}</ref>

===1966â€“1968: "Don't Touch Me" and breakthrough===
{{Listen
| filename = Jeannie Seely--Don't Touch Me--Audio File.ogg
| title = "Don't Touch Me"
| description = Seely's signature song, which won a [[Grammy Award]] in 1966.
}}
Cochran brought a [[demo (music)|demo]] of Seely's voice to all of Nashville's record labels and each of them passed on signing her.{{sfn|Homer|2019|p=42}} According to Seely, [[Fred Foster]] of [[Monument Records]] was interested in signing her if she found a quality song to record. Now traveling as part of Porter Wagoner's road show, Seely received a phone call from Cochran while performing in [[Rochester, New York]]. Cochran performed the first verse for her on the phone and Seely agreed to hearing the remainder of the song in-person. Cochran then flew to Rochester where he played her the remaining verses and Seely decided to record it.<ref name="Grizzly">{{cite web |title=Exclusive Interview with Country Legend Jeannie Seely |url=https://grizzlyrose.com/interview-jeannie-seely/ |website=Grizzly Rose |date=17 January 2017 |access-date=25 July 2024}}</ref> Cochran then brought Seely to Foster's Nashville office and he signed her to a contract with Monument.{{sfn|Homer|2019|p=42}} Released as a single in 1966, "Don't Touch Me" rose to number two on the US [[Hot Country Songs]] chart,<ref name="Country Songs">{{cite magazine |title=Jeannie Seely chart history (country songs) |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/jeannie-seely/chart-history/csi/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=25 July 2024}}</ref> number 85 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Jeannie Seely chart history (Hot 100) |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/jeannie-seely/chart-history/csi/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=25 July 2024}}</ref> and number 29 on the US [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|adult contemporary]] chart.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Jeannie Seely chart history (Adult Contemporary) |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/jeannie-seely/chart-history/csi/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=25 July 2024}}</ref> Writers and historians have since called "Don't Touch Me" a country music standard.<ref name="PBS"/><ref name="Top Five">{{cite web |last1=Horton |first1=Carrie |title=Top 5 Jeannie Seely Songs |url=https://theboot.com/top-5-jeannie-seely-songs/ |website=The Boot |date=6 July 2023 |access-date=25 July 2024}}</ref>

Now a popular concert attraction, Seely was replaced by [[Dolly Parton]] in Porter Wagoner's road and television show.{{sfn|Homer|2019|p=42}} The success of "Don't Touch Me" also brought Seely the [[Best Female Country Vocal Performance]] accolade at the [[9th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref name="Grammys">{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely: Artist |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/jeannie-seely |website=[[Grammy Awards]] |date=19 November 2019 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> She was later invited to become a member of the [[Grand Ole Opry]] in 1967.<ref name="Opry">{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely -- Grand Ole Opry |url=https://www.opry.com/artists/jeannie-seely/ |website=[[Grand Ole Opry]] |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> The song led to the release of her debut studio album called ''[[The Seely Style]]'',<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''[[The Seely Style]]'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Monument Records]] |date=September 1966 |id=MLP-8057 (LP mono); SLP-18057 (LP stereo)}}</ref> which rose into the top ten on the US [[Top Country Albums]] chart in 1966.<ref name="Country Albums">{{cite magazine |title=Jeannie Seely chart history: Country Albums |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/jeannie-seely/chart-history/clp/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> Seely's next two single releases also made the US country top 20: "[[It's Only Love (Jeannie Seely song)|It's Only Love]]" (1966) and "[[A Wanderin' Man]]" (1967).<ref name="Country Songs"/> The latter releases (along with additional Monument tracks) were composed by Cochran, whom she married in the late 1960s.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=301}} Seely paid tribute to him with her second studio LP, ''[[Thanks, Hank!]]'', which consisted of songs all written by Cochran.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''[[Thanks, Hank!]]'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Monument Records]] |date=May 1967 |id=MLP-8073 (LP Mono); SLP-18073 (LP Stereo)}}</ref> The LP made the top 20 of the US country albums chart in 1967.<ref name="Country Albums"/>

In the late sixties, Seely's US touring schedule increased and she traveled frequently from coast-to-coast.{{sfn|Harman|Seely|2002|p=3}} In 1967, alongside [[Ernest Tubb]] and often appeared on his country music television program.<ref name="Jack Greene Jeannie Seely">{{cite journal |last1=Greene |first1=Jack |last2=Seely |first2=Jeannie |title=''[[Jack Greene, Jeannie Seely]]'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=January 1970 |id=DL-75171 (LP Stereo)}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Haislop |first1=Nia |last2=Lathrop |first2=Tad |last3=Sumrall |first3=Harry |title=Giants of Country Music Classic Sounds and Stars, from the Heart of Nashville to the Top of the Charts |date=1995 |publisher=Billboard Books |isbn=978-0823076352 |page=75}}</ref> Furthermore, Seely's next single "[[I'll Love You More (Than You Need)]]" rose to number ten on the US country chart in 1968.<ref name="Country Songs"/> It served as the title track to her [[I'll Love You More|1968 studio album]], which climbed into US country albums top 30 in 1968.<ref name="Country Albums"/> Before the end of 1968, her next two singles reached the top 40 of the Hot Country Songs chart: "[[Welcome Home to Nothing]]" and "[[How Is He?]]".<ref name="Country Songs"/> Both songs appeared on her fourth studio offering ''[[Little Things (Jeannie Seely album)|Little Things]]'',<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''[[Little Things (Jeannie Seely album)|Little Things]]'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Monument Records]] |date=December 1968 |id=SLP-18104}}</ref> her fourth album to make the Top Country Albums chart.<ref name="Country Albums"/> Commenting on her Monument recordings, writers and critics found Seely's vocals to demonstrate "raw emotion", "suffering" and "soul"<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Country Reviews: The Cash Box Bullseye |magazine=[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]] |date=February 25, 1967 |page=56 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Cash-Box-IDX/60s/1967/CB-1967-02-25-OCR-Page-0056.pdf#search=%22jeannie%20seely%20when%20it's%20over%201967%22 |access-date=24 July 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Spotlight Singles: Top 20 Country |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=June 1, 1968 |page=77 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Billboard-Index/IDX/1968/Billboard%201968-06-01-OCR-Page-0099.pdf#search=%22jeannie%20seely%20how%20is%20he?%20spotlight%22 |access-date=24 July 2024}}</ref> while others found her singing style to steer towards [[Pop music|pop]] music.<ref name="Thanks Hank">{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Greg |title=''Thanks, Hank!'' -- Jeannie Seely -- Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/thanks-hank%21-mw0000967234 |website=[[Allmusic]] |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>

===1969â€“1977: Duets with Jack Greene and solo career comeback===
In 1969, Seely signed with [[Decca Records]] and began recording alongside producer [[Owen Bradley]]. Her debut label single was "Just Enough to Start Me Dreamin'",<ref name="Decca">{{cite magazine |title=Country and Western: Decca Signs Jeannie Seely |magazine=[[Record World]] |date=February 15, 1969 |page=50 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Record-World-IDX/IDX/60s/69/Record-World-1969-02-15-OCR-Page-0050.pdf#search=%22jeannie%20seely%20signs%20with%20decca%22 |access-date=26 July 2024}}</ref> which peaked outside the US country songs top 40 in 1969.<ref name="Country Songs"/> The label issued her [[Jeannie Seely (1969 album)|eponymous studio album]] in April 1969, featuring the single, along with several cover tunes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''[[Jeannie Seely (1969 album)|Jeannie Seely]]'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=April 1969 |id=DL-75093}}</ref> Seely also agreed to a tour of [[Far East|eastern Asia]] in January 1969 where she performed at US [[military base]]s<ref name="Bases">{{cite magazine |title=Jeannie Tours Bases |journal=[[Record World]] |date=November 30, 1968 |page=49 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Record-World-IDX/IDX/60s/68/RW-1968-11-30-OCR-Page-0045.pdf#search=%22jeannie%20seely%20army%20tour%22 |access-date=26 July 2024}}</ref> for a total of six-weeks.<ref name="Decca"/> She also became the host of a 30-minute radio segment on the [[American Forces Network|American Armed Forces Network]] that attracted four million listeners<ref name="Bases"/> and according to ''Billboard'', made her the first female military disc jockey.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Jeannie Seely 1st Country Female DJ to Do Army Show |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=December 14, 1968 |page=29 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Billboard-Index/IDX/1968/Billboard%201968-12-14-OCR-Page-0029.pdf#search=%22jeannie%20seely%20signs%20with%20decca%22 |access-date=26 July 2024}}</ref> Decca issued Seely's next studio album in 1970 titled ''[[Please Be My New Love]]'' which also included mostly cover songs.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''[[Please Be My New Love]]'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=June 1970 |id=DL-75228}}</ref> Among them was the title track (which was a top 50 country single)<ref name="Country Songs"/> and a medley arranged by Bradley titled "Jeannie's Song" that featured Seely singing portions of different country songs from the period.{{sfn|Homer|2019|p=43}}

[[File:Jeannie and Jack 060811 at R.O.P.E. Event 1.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Seely and [[Jack Greene]] onstage in the early 2010s. For several years, the pair recorded and toured together.]]

Through Seely's association with [[Ernest Tubb]], she formed a duet partnership with fellow Decca artist [[Jack Greene]].<ref name="Jack Greene Jeannie Seely"/> The duo's first single, "[[Wish I Didn't Have to Miss You]]", reached the US country top five 1970<ref name="Country Songs"/> and received a country duet nomination at the [[12th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref name="Grammys"/> It was then featured on their 1970 [[Jack Greene, Jeannie Seely|studio album]] of duet recordings<ref name="Jack Greene Jeannie Seely"/> Greene and Seely then formed a road show that routinely played venues across North America and Europe,{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=302-303}}{{sfn|Homer|2019|p=43}} including New York City's [[Madison Square Garden]] and London's [[Wembley Arena]].{{sfn|Homer|2019|p=43}} Their second duet album together, ''[[Two for the Show (Jack Greene and Jeannie Seely album)|Two for the Show]]'' (1973), was named for their collaborative road appearances.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Greene |first1=Jack |last2=Seely |first2=Jeannie |title=''[[Two for the Show (Jack Greene and Jeannie Seely album)|Two for the Show]]'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=January 1973 |id=DL-75392}}</ref> The Greene-Seely duo had two more top 20 singles on the US and Canadian ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' country charts through 1973: "[[Much Oblige]]" and "[[What in the World Has Gone Wrong with Our Love]]".<ref name="Country Songs"/><ref name=cancountry>{{cite magazine|title=Search results for "Jeannie Seely" under Country Singles|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=5cc1co3unir7jujspt8uvvkh86&q1=Jeannie+Seely&q2=Country+Singles&interval=20|magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|accessdate=24 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402142234/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=5cc1co3unir7jujspt8uvvkh86&q1=Jeannie+Seely&q2=Country+Singles&interval=20|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Greene and Seely were also nominated four times for the [[Country Music Association]]'s "Vocal Duo of the Year" award between 1972 and 1975.<ref name="CMA">{{cite web |title=Past Winners and Nominees: Jeannie Seely |url=https://cmaawards.com/past-winners-and-nominees/?appSession=9093S4929571M1IR18576495GF10XXQOHK9Q8IE3DCMYFEIWZ17E3C90JMWMD00EM851M17AYT2RLA7WU18V8EWMT89ZUJHXFQ73I8Y0Q756132V0B6HN29R170AV729 |website=[[Country Music Association Awards]] |access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>

Seely's solo career also continued simultaneously during this period.<ref name="Allmusic Bio"/> Her solo releases through 1972 ("Tell Me Again", "You Don't Understand Him Like I Do", "Alright I'll Sign the Papers", "[[Pride (Ray Price song)|Pride]]" and "Farm in Pennsyltucky") reached lower-peaking positions on the US country chart.<ref name="Country Songs"/> Yet, she found success writing [[Faron Young]]'s single "Leavin' and Sayin' Goodbye", which made the country top ten in 1972.{{sfn|Homer|2019|p=43}} [[Walter Haynes]] then produced Seely's 1973 single, "[[Can I Sleep in Your Arms]]".<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Country Music Report: Country Artist of the Week: Jeannie Seely |magazine=[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]] |date=September 8, 1973 |page=33 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Cash-Box-IDX/70s/1973/Cash-Box-1973-09-08-OCR-Page-0033.pdf#search=%22jeannie%20seely%22 |access-date=26 July 2024}}</ref> A reworked version of a traditional folk ballad,{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=302}} "Can I Sleep in Your Arms" reached the top ten on both the US and Canadian country charts<ref name="Country Songs"/><ref name="cancountry"/> and became her highest-peaking single in the US since 1970.<ref name="Country Songs"/> An adapted version of another folk ballad ("[[Come All You Fair and Tender Ladies]]") called "[[Lucky Ladies]]"{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=302}} reached the US and Canadian country songs top 20 in 1974.<ref name="Country Songs"/><ref name="cancountry"/> Both appeared on her next studio LP, ''[[Can I Sleep in Your Arms/Lucky Ladies]]'', which also collected her previous chart singles<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''[[Can I Sleep in Your Arms/Lucky Ladies]]'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[MCA Records]] |date=November 1973 |id=MCA-385 (LP Stereo)}}</ref> and rose to number 15 on the US country albums chart in 1973.<ref name="Country Albums"/>

Seely's next two 1974 recordings titled "[[I Miss You (Jeannie Seely song)|I Miss You]]" and "[[He Can Be Mine]]" reached the US country top 40, while "He Can Be Mine" made the Canadian country top 20.<ref name="Country Songs"/><ref name="cancountry"/> She then moved to [[Columbia Records]] in 1977 where she was produced by [[Tompall & the Glaser Brothers|Chuck Glaser]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Columbia Signs Seely |magazine=[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]] |date=June 4, 1977 |page=28 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Cash-Box-IDX/70s/1977/CB-1977-06-04-OCR-Page-0028.pdf#search=%22jeannie%20seely%20columbia%20records%201977%22 |access-date=26 July 2024}}</ref> The label issued her last charting US country songs: "Take Me to Bed" and "We're Still Hangin' in There Ain't We Jessi".<ref name="Country Songs"/> The latter recording described the marriages of country artists [[Jessi Colter]], [[Jan Howard]], [[Dottie West]] and [[Tammy Wynette]].{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=302}} The same year, the Greene-Seely duo released a [[live album|live LP]] titled ''Live at the Grand Ole Opry''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Greene |first1=Jack |last2=Seely |first2=Jeannie |title=''Live at the Grand Ole Opry'' (Disc Information) |journal=[[Pinnacle Records]] |date=May 29, 1978 |id=RDS-203}}</ref> Seely's songs were again being recorded by other artists during this period. This included [[Merle Haggard]] (who recorded "Life of a Rodeo Cowboy" for his [[I'm Always on a Mountain When I Fall|1977 album]])<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Haggard |first1=Merle |title=''[[I'm Always on a Mountain When I Fall]]'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[MCA Records]] |date=June 1978 |id=MCA-2375 (LP Stereo)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Horton |first1=Carrie |title=Jeannie Seely Recalls the Conversation That Inspired 'Life of a Rodeo Cowboy' |url=https://theboot.com/jeannie-seely-life-of-a-rodeo-cowboy-inspiration/ |website=The Boot |date=10 January 2017 |access-date=26 July 2024}}</ref> and [[Ernest Tubb]] (who recorded the 1977 single "Sometimes I Do")<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tubb |first1=Ernest |title="Sometimes I Do"/"Half My Heart's in Texas" (7" vinyl single) |journal=First Generation Records |date=1977 |id=FGS-001}}</ref> In 1977, she was injured in a car accident.<ref name="Allmusic Bio"/>

===1978â€“2009: Career setbacks, acting and return to recording===
[[File:Jeannie in Could It Be Love.jpg|thumb|right|160px|Seely started dabbling in acting during the 1980s, particularly in stage productions. In 2005, she portrayed the character of Mabel in the play ''Could It Be Love''.]]
Seely's career several setbacks following her car accident.<ref name="Allmusic Bio"/> Her performance opportunities became limited and she divorced Hank Cochran.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=302}} Despite [[re-recording (music)|re-recording]] her duets for a 1982 album with Jack Greene,<ref name="Allmusic Bio"/> the duo ended their partnership during this period.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gibbons |first1=Annette |title=My 15 Minutes With the Fabulous Jeannie Seely at CRS 2020 |url=https://thinkcountrymusic.com/whats-new/my-15-minutes-with-the-fabulous-jeannie-seely-at-crs-2020/ |website=Think Country Music |access-date=29 July 2024}}</ref> In an interview, Seely theorized that promoters were more "loyal" to Greene, leading to him receiving more concert offers than she did.<ref name="Grizzly"/> Yet, Seely did appear alongside [[Willie Nelson]] in the [[Honeysuckle Rose (album)|soundtrack]] of the 1980 film ''[[Honeysuckle Rose (film)|Honeysuckle Rose]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Album Reviews |magazine=[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]] |date=August 30, 1980 |page=42 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Cash-Box-IDX/80s/1980/CB-1980-08-30-OCR-Page-0042.pdf#search=%22jeannie%20seely%20honeysuckle%20rose%22 |access-date=29 July 2024}}</ref> She also started touring alongside Nelson in his "Willie Nelson and Family" show, including at the 1982 Tennessee State Fair.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Collie |first1=Biff |title=Inside Nashville |magazine=[[Radio & Records]] |date=October 1, 1982 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-RandR-IDX/IDX/80s/82/RR-1982-10-01-OCR-Page-0030.pdf#search=%22jeannie%20seely%20willie%20nelson%20opening%22 |access-date=29 July 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Talent & Venues: Boxscore |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=October 2, 1982 |page=49 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Billboard-Index/IDX/1982/1982-10-02-Billboard-Page-0077.pdf#search=%22jeannie%20seely%20willie%20nelson%20opening%22 |access-date=29 July 2024}}</ref> In 1985, she opened up a Nashville nightclub named "Jeannie Seely's Country Club".<ref>{{cite web |title=Nashville Then: Best of 1985 Music |url=https://www.tennessean.com/picture-gallery/news/local/2015/12/30/nashville-then-best-of-1985-music/78080448/ |website=[[The Tennessean]] |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> The club closed down after only a year of being open to the public.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=302}} The same year, [[Little Jimmy Dickens]] released the album ''Country Music Hall of Fame'', which was produced by Seely.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dickens |first1=Little Jimmy |title=''Country Music Hall of Fame'' (Liner Notes) |journal=Tater-Patch Records |date=1985 |id=MD-101}}</ref>

Seely then dabbled in acting, first appearing in the country music-themed musical, ''Takin' It Home'' (1986). Seely played alongside [[Lorrie Morgan]] and [[Jean Shepard]] during the show's run.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=302}} In 1988, she played the character of Miss Mona in the Nashville-based Circle Players' revival of ''[[The Best Little Whorehouse in Texas]]''.<ref name="Over the Years">{{cite news |title=Jeannie Seely Over the Years |url=https://www.tennessean.com/picture-gallery/entertainment/music/2017/09/14/jeannie-seely-over-the-years/105603070/ |access-date=29 July 2024 |work=[[The Tennessean]] |date=July 1, 2020}}</ref> She later appeared in her first straight-acting role for the 1990 production ''Everybody Loves Opal''. During rehearsal, she broke two of her ribs but still performed for the show's duration at a Nashville dinner theater.<ref name="ARH">{{cite web |title=Opry Magazine: Jeannie Seely |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Stations/IDX/Station-Magazines-IDX/WSM-Opry/Opry-1994-OCR-Page-0110.pdf |website=American Radio History |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> Seely also appeared on country music television programs during the 1980s, including interviewing performers on ''Opry Backstage''.{{sfn|Homer|2019|p=43}}

Seely returned to recording with the release of her second eponymous studio album in 1990. The ten-track project was self-produced and featured self-written compositions, along with a cover of [[Michael Bolton]]'s "[[When I'm Back on My Feet Again]]".<ref name="Eponymous Album">{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Jeannie Seely'' (Disc Information) |journal=Self Released |date=1990 |id=BO-438 (cassette)}}</ref> She then appeared alongside [[Stonewall Jackson (musician)|Stonewall Jackson]] in the 1993 music video for [[Confederate Railroad]]'s "[[Trashy Women]]".<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Morris |first1=Edward |title=Nashville Scene |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=July 10, 1993 |page=24}}</ref> Her first album of [[Christmas music]] was released in 1996 titled ''[[Number One Christmas]]''.<ref name="Allmusic Bio"/> Consisting of spiritual holiday songs, the album was first released by the Power Pak label, but later re-released under the title ''Golden Christmas'' in 2007.<ref name="Number One Christmas">{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Number One Christmas'' (Liner Notes) |journal=Power Pak Records |date=October 1, 1996 |id=PKCD-10512 (CD)}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''A Golden Christmas'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Gusto Records]] |date=October 7, 2007 |id=GT7-0818-2 (CD)}}</ref> Seely then released her 1999 studio album called ''Been There...Sung That!'', an album of cover tunes that also featured Willie Nelson and [[T. Graham Brown]].<ref name="Been There Sung That">{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Been There...Sung That!'' (Disc Information) |journal=Shadpoke Records |date=June 1999 |id=1557 (compact disc)}}</ref> In 2001, Seely contributed to [[Ralph Stanley]]'s studio album ''Clinch Mountain Sweethearts''<ref>{{cite web |title=''Clinch Mountain Sweethearts'': Ralph Stanley: Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/clinch-mountain-sweethearts-mw0000014135 |website=[[Allmusic]] |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> and followed it with her next studio album in 2003 called ''[[Life's Highway (Jeannie Seely album)|Life's Highway]]''.<ref name="Allmusic Bio"/> John Lupton of ''Country Standard Time'' praised Seely's vocal contributions, calling it "classic country" and "timeless".<ref name="Country Standard Time">{{cite web |last1=Lupton |first1=John |title=Jeannie Seely travels life's highways |url=https://www.countrystandardtime.com/d/article.asp?xid=734 |website=Country Standard Time |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Bob Mitchell of the ''Louisville Music News'' wrote, "Overall, this recording lacks the earthy intensity and drive that characterizes authentic traditional Bluegrass. But, make no mistake, ''Life's Highway'' is enjoyable and features some of country and bluegrass's finest musicians," he wrote.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mitchell |first1=Bob |title=Keeping it Real Life's Highway (OMS) Jeannie Seely |url=http://www.louisvillemusicnews.net/webmanager/index.php?WEB_CAT_ID=50&storyid=2900&headline=Jeannie_Seely_-_Life%27s_Highway&issueid=183 |website=Louisville Music News |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>

Seely also continued acting, playing the role of Louise Seger in the 2001 musical ''Always Patsy Cline''. The show chronicled the friendship between [[Patsy Cline]] and Seger.<ref name="Always PC">{{cite web |last1=Elkins |first1=Ashley |title=8/17/01 Community season |url=https://www.djournal.com/news/community-season/article_1b74fbf7-8698-597d-ae06-90edbdf5737e.html |website=[[Northeast Mississippi Daily Journal]] |date=17 August 2001 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> In 2002, Seely played the role of Mrs. Jenkins in the film ''Changing Hearts'', which starred [[Faye Dunaway]].<ref name="Allmovie">{{cite web |last1=Erickson |first1=Hal |title=''Changing Hearts'' (2002) |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/changing-hearts-v296532 |website=[[Allmovie]] |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> Seely then performed Nashville's production of the sexually-themed ''[[The Vagina Monologues]]'' alongside fellow country artists [[Kathy Mattea]] and [[Pam Tillis]].<ref name="Nashville Scene">{{cite web |last1=Brady |first1=Martin |title=Not Your Father's Opry Star |url=https://www.nashvillescene.com/arts-culture/article/13011417/not-your-fathers-opry-star |website=[[Nashville Scene]] |date=24 February 2005 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> She then starred in the musical ''Could It Be Love'' from 2004-2007, which included a performance at Nashville's [[Ryman Auditorium]]. Seely portrayed an older theater actress that wanted to put on a senior citizen version of ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]''.<ref name="Out and About">{{cite web |last1=Breegle |first1=Ryan |title=Riggan's hit musical 'Could It Be Love?' returns to Nashville |url=https://outandaboutnashville.com/riggans-hit-musical-could-it-be-love-returns-to-nashville/ |website=Out and About Nashville |date=September 2005 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely Interview |url=https://www.countrystarscentral.com/jeannieseelyinterview.htm |website=Country Stars Central |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> As the 2000s continued, Seely recalled on her website playing shows at the [[Dollywood]] theme park, as well as in Ireland and on country music cruises.{{sfn|Seely|Harman|2002|p=6}}

===2010â€“present: Continued recording and other projects===
In 2010, Seely's Nashville home was destroyed in the [[2010 Tennessee floods]] but she resumed her career, beginning with an Opry performance shortly after the natural disaster occurred.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dignan |first1=Sara |title=How the Grand Ole Opry Survived the Historic Nashville Floods |url=https://www.wideopencountry.com/nashville-floods-grand-ole-opry/ |website=Wide Open Country |date=17 November 2017 |access-date=1 August 2024}}</ref> Yet Through her own label (Cheyenne Records), Seely issued her next studio project in 2011 called ''Vintage Country: Old But Treasured''. Another self-produced project, ''Vintage Country'' contained 11 tracks of traditional country songs she chose to cover.<ref name="Vintage Country">{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Vintage Country: Old But Treasured'' (Disc Information) |journal=Cheyenne Records |date=February 1, 2011 |id=23468942 (CD)}}</ref> According to Seely, she named it ''Vintage Country'' after making several jokes during performances about classic country music.<ref name="Discography">{{cite web |title=Discography |url=https://www.jeannieseely.com/discography.cfm#vintage_country |website=Jeannie Seely.com |access-date=1 August 2024}}</ref>

[[File:Jeannie on Opry 040818.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Seely at the [[Grand Ole Opry]], 2010s]]
Seely maintained a continued presence at the Grand Ole Opry during the 2010s decade by performing and interviewing other artists onstage. She also made appearances at Nashville's [[CMA Music Festival]] during this period as well.<ref name="Over the Years"/> She also began hosting the "Dottie West Birthday Bash" in 2016, which is held every October in honor of West and supports the Nashville Musicians Relief Fund.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Papadatos |first1=Markos |title=Jeannie Seely Talks Dottie West Birthday Bash, Bill Anderson |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/music/jeannie-seely-talks-dottie-west-birthday-bash-bill-anderson/article/555817 |website=Digital Journal |date=13 August 2019 |access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref> Her next studio project ''[[Written in Song]]'' (2017) featured self-written songs that were first cut by other recording artists.<ref name="Allmusic Bio"/> Included were Seely's interpretations of "Anyone Knows What Love Is Will Understand", "Leaving and Saying Goodbye" and "Senses".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nicholson |first1=Jessica |title=Jeannie Seely Celebrates Release of 'Written In Song' |url=https://musicrow.com/2017/01/jeannie-seely-celebrates-release-of-written-in-song/ |website=Music Row |date=13 January 2017 |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> Markos Papadatos of the ''Digital Journal'' gave the album an "A" rating and commented, "'Miss Country Soul' is back stronger than ever. There is a variety on her latest musical effort."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Papadatos |first1=Markos |title=Jeannie Seely soars on new country album ''Written in Song'' |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/music/review-jeannie-seely-soars-on-new-country-album-written-in-song/article/483167#ixzz6JjY2hqQm |website=Digital Journal |date=8 January 2017 |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>

In 2018, it was announced that Seely would join [[Willie Nelson]]'s [[Sirius XM]] radio series, ''[[Willie's Roadhouse]]''.<ref name="Sirius">{{cite web |last1=Hollabaugh |first1=Lorie |title=Jeannie Seely Joins Willie's Roadhouse Family On SiriusXM |url=https://musicrow.com/2018/05/jeannie-seely-joins-willies-roadhouse-family-on-siriusxm/ |website=Music Row |date=24 May 2018 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> Her segment, titled "Sunday's with Seely"<ref name="Meadville"/> has since aired on the network on Sunday's from noon to 4pm. During her segment, Seely shares stories from her memories in Nashville and also plays songs by classic country artists.<ref>{{cite web |title=SiriusXM Announces The Addition of Jeannie Seely To The Willie's Roadhouse Family As An On Air Personality |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/SiriusXM-Announces-The-Addition-of-Jeannie-Seely-To-The-Willies-Roadhouse-Family-As-An-On-Air-Personality-20180524 |website=[[BroadwayWorld]]}}</ref> In late 2019, Seely announced her next studio offering called ''[[An American Classic]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=LMU Honors Jeannie Seely With Honorary Doctorate of Arts Degree |url=https://www.musicconnection.com/lmu-honors-jeannie-seely-honorary-doctorate-arts-degree/ |website=Music Connection |date=16 December 2019 |access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> The album released in August 2020 shortly after she celebrated her 80th birthday. Produced by [[Don Cusic]] and issued on [[Curb Records]], ''An American Classic'' included several new recordings and featured guest performers like Willie Nelson, [[Rhonda Vincent]] and [[Steve Wariner]].<ref name="SLN">{{cite news |last1=Evans Price |first1=Deborah |title=Jeannie Seely Delivers On New Album, 'An American Classic' |url=https://www.soundslikenashville.com/news/jeannie-seely-delivers-on-new-album-an-american-classic/ |access-date=24 July 2024 |work=Sounds Like Nashville}}</ref> Tom Netherland of the ''[[Bristol Herald Courier]]'' found the album cemented Seely as a significant female country artist<ref name="Herald">{{cite web |last1=Netherland |first1=Tom |title=Jeannie Seely releases new album, 'An American Classic' |url=https://heraldcourier.com/townnews/music/jeannie-seely-releases-new-album-an-american-classic/article_c11d9d4b-22dc-58c7-b0c3-8dcde12fc321.html |website=[[Bristol Herald Courier]] |date=13 August 2020 |access-date=15 August 2020}}</ref> while Markos Papadatos of ''Digital Journal'' gave the project an "A" rating.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Papadatos |first1=Markos |title=Review: Jeannie Seely releases amazing album 'An American Classic' |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/music/review-jeannie-seely-releases-amazing-album-an-american-classic/article/576350#ixzz6V90TZFMC |website=Digital Journal |date=14 August 2020 |access-date=15 August 2020}}</ref> After receiving praise from singing a cover of Dottie West's "Suffertime" on the Opry, Seely went into RCA Studio B to record her own version of the song. The song was released in July 2024, along with a corresponding video showcasing the recording process.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Watts |first1=Cindy |title=Jeannie Seely, Country Music's Oldest Working Woman, Says She's 'Recreating History' with New Song (Exclusive) |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=July 19, 2024 |url=https://people.com/jeannie-seely-new-song-suffertime-dottie-west-exclusive-8681009 |access-date=1 August 2024}}</ref>

==Personal life==
===Car accident and health===
In June 1977, Seely was involved in a car accident in [[Goodlettsville, Tennessee]] (located outside of Nashville) after her vehicle crashed into a tree. She was admitted to Nashville Memorial Hospital, suffering a fractured jaw, broken ribs,<ref name="NY Times">{{cite news |last1=Krebbs |first1=Albin |title=Notes on People |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/06/30/archives/westchester-opinion-notes-on-people.html |access-date=15 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 30, 1977}}</ref> a punctured lung and a collapsed lung. Upon arriving at the hospital she was given same-day surgery to repair her lung.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Indiana Gazette from Indiana Pennsylvania [title unknown] |publisher=[[Indiana Gazette]] |date=June 29, 1977}}</ref> She was reported in "fair condition"<ref name="NY Times"/> and eventually recovered from her injuries.<ref name="Allmusic Bio"/> Friend Dottie West helped Seely following her hospital release, helping her when she was immobile and taking her on car rides for a change in scenery.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thanki |first1=Juli |title=Country Trailblazer Dottie West Remembered |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/08/26/country-trailblazer-dottie-west-remembered/88531556/ |website=[[The Tennessean]] |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Seely later reflected that the accident brought her a new appreciation for life. "You know, it sounds like a cliche, but it's true that your perspective changes when you have a close call, what you took for granted you come to appreciate more,"{{sfn|Seely|Harman|2002|p=5}}

In 2024, Seely was hospitalized in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]] after suffering from "acute diverticulitis" and "dehydration" on a trip to her home town. She was later released and was reportedly "doing well".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liptak |first1=Carena |title=Jeannie Seely Hospitalized in Pennsylvania |url=https://tasteofcountry.com/jeannie-seely-hospitalized/ |website=[[Taste of Country]] |date=12 August 2024 |access-date=13 August 2024}}</ref>

===Marriages and homes===
[[File:Hank Cochran.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Seely was first married to songwriter [[Hank Cochran]]. It was Cochran who wrote many of her biggest hits.]]
Seely has been married twice. Her first marriage was to her songwriter Hank Cochran,<ref name="The Guardian">{{cite web |last1=Russell |first1=Tony |title=Hank Cochran obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jul/21/hank-cochran-obituary |website=[[The Guardian]] |date=21 July 2010 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |last1=Hackette |first1=Vernell |title=Hank Cochran Documentary Spotlights Songwriter's Legacy |url=https://theboot.com/hank-cochran-documentary/ |website=The Boot |date=26 April 2012 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> whom she officially wed on June 15, 1969 in [[Renfro Valley, Kentucky]] in a church ceremony.<ref>{{cite magazine  |last1=Briggs |first1=Eddie |title=Hank, Jeannie, Wed in 'Chapel' |magazine=[[Record World]] |date=July 12, 1969 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Record-World-IDX/IDX/60s/69/RW-1969-07-12-OCR-Page-0053.pdf#search=%22jeannie%20seely%20hank%20cochran%22 |access-date=13 August 2024}}</ref> Around 1975, the couple built a home<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Red O'Donnell's Year in Review |magazine=[[Record World]] |date=October 18, 1975 |page=70 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Record-World-IDX/IDX/70s/75/RW-1975-10-18-OCR-Page-0090.pdf#search=%22jeannie%20seely%20hank%20cochran%22 |access-date=13 August 2024}}</ref> set on a farm with 77 acres of property in [[Hendersonville, Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Country Roundup |magazine=[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]] |date=May 10, 1975 |page=27 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Cash-Box-IDX/70s/1975/CB-1975-05-10-OCR-Page-0027.pdf#search=%22jeannie%20seely%20hank%20cochran%22 |access-date=13 August 2024}}</ref>
In the late 1970s, the couple separated<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cackett |first1=Alan |title=Hank Cochran: A Songwriter's Way of Life |journal=Country Music People |date=December 1981 |pages=36â€“38}}</ref> and officially filed for divorced in 1979.<ref name="Guardian">{{cite news |last1=Russell |first1=Tony |title=Hank Cochran Obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jul/21/hank-cochran-obituary |access-date=13 August 2024 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=July 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Friskics Warren |first1=Bill |title=Hank Cochran, Writer for Country Music Stars, Dies at 74 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/17/arts/music/17cochran.html |access-date=13 August 2024 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 17, 2010}}</ref> Cochran died in 2010.<ref name="Guardian"/> Seely later stated that Cochran helped lay "the groundwork" for country music in a 2012 documentary about his life.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hackette |first1=Vernell |title=Hank Cochran Documentary Spotlights Songwriter's Legacy |url=https://theboot.com/hank-cochran-documentary/ |website=The Boot |date=26 April 2012 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>

Seely continued to live in the farmhouse until the early 1990s when she decided to move to a smaller cottage home, located on the [[Cumberland River]] in Nashville.<ref name="Grizzly"/> It was later destroyed in the [[2010 Tennessee floods]]. As the water started to rise in her neighborhood, Seely and her husband escaped in a pickup truck, leaving valuables behind. Seely lost most possessions in her home after three feet of water had damaged the inside.<ref name="Floods">{{cite web |last1=Hackett |first1=Vernell |title=Jeannie Seely Rebuilds Life and Career One Year After the Floods |url=https://theboot.com/jeannie-seely-interview/ |website=The Boot |date=2 May 2011 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> "You can either laugh about it or you can cry, and I don't feel like crying," she said in a performance shortly after losing her home.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Talbott |first1=Chris |title=Despite Floods, Grand Ole Opry Goes On |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/37115999/ns/nbc_nightly_news_with_brian_williams/t/despite-floods-grand-ole-opry-goes/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200814060056/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/37115999/ns/nbc_nightly_news_with_brian_williams/t/despite-floods-grand-ole-opry-goes/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 14, 2020 |website=[[NBC News]] |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> She credited the help of local volunteers with helping to clean up her home which she ultimately moved back into.<ref name="Floods"/>

Seely married Nashville attorney Gene Ward in 2010 as well.<ref name="Crawford"/> A year later, Seely cancelled several engagements after Ward was rushed to the hospital shortly before she was scheduled to make a Grand Ole Opry appearance. She later posted on social media that Ward's condition improved and he was able to start the recovery process.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Despres |first1=Tricia |title=A country music legend asks for prayers for her ailing husband |url=https://rarecountry.com/news/a-country-music-legend-asks-for-prayers-for-her-ailing-husband/ |website=Rare Country |date=February 2018 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> The couple renewed their wedding vows in 2019 on a country music cruise. "The reason Gene and I wanted to renew our vows is because first of all, we can...I thought it might be nice for them [her fans] to see Gene standing up there looking so sharp in his suit," she commented..<ref>{{cite web |last1=Baxter |first1=Lou |title=Townville native in Grand Ole Opry renews wedding vows |url=https://www.yourerie.com/news/local-news/townville-native-in-grand-ole-opry-renews-wedding-vows/ |website=Your Erie.com |date=8 February 2019 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>

==Artistry==
{{quote box|quote="In 1966, Seely's '[[Don't Touch Me]]' took country women's sexuality from the [[honky-tonk]] into the bedroom even though it didn't end up there, and the on-again off-again ache in her voice retained its savor afterwards. But never again did she find a song at once so moral and so febrile."|source=â€”''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]'' (1981)<ref name="CG">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|author-link=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=089919026X|chapter=Consumer Guide '70s: S|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_chap.php?k=S&bk=70|access-date=March 12, 2019}}</ref>|width=25%|align=right|style=padding:8px;}}

Seely's musical style has categorized and identified with the country genre,<ref name="Allmusic Bio"/><ref name="Top 5">{{cite web |last1=Horton |first1=Carrie |title=Top 5 Jeannie Seely Songs |url=https://theboot.com/top-5-jeannie-seely-songs/ |website=The Boot |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> while also incorporating elements of [[Pop music|pop]]<ref name="Thanks Hank"/> and [[Soul music|soul]].<ref name="Top 5">{{cite web |last1=Horton |first1=Carrie |title=Top 5 Jeannie Seely Songs |url=https://theboot.com/top-5-jeannie-seely-songs/ |website=The Boot |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> Critics and writers named her "Miss Country Soul" due to not only her style but her emotional vocal performances.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=300-301}}<ref name="PBS"/> Writers [[Robert K. Oermann]] and Mary A. Bufwack wrote, "Jeannie's husky cigarette-stained voice moaned with such agony"{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=301}} In reference to her nickname, [[Ken Burns]] of [[PBS]] called her singing "big heart" and "emotion-packed".<ref name="PBS"/>

Seely's music has also varied in subject matter. In "Don't Touch Me", Seely's character eludes to themes of sexuality and desire.<ref name="Top 5"/> Oermann and Bufwack found it to be "a throbbing song of unfulfilled passion"{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=301}} while ''The Boot'''s Carrie Horton found the song proved "that women can sing about sex too".<ref name="Top 5"/> Music critic [[Robert Christgau]] also highlighted a sexually-charged story line.<ref name="CG"/> Other songs with a similar theme included 1977's "Take Me to Bed".{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=302}} The subjects of Seely's other singles included heartache and love lost such as in "It's Only Love" and "Can I Sleep in Your Arms".<ref name="Top 5"/>{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=302}} Other topics she has explored in songs include [[recreational drug use]], notably in "[[Written in Song|Who Needs You]]".{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=302}}

Seely was influenced by country music from an early age, beginning with an interest in the Grand Ole Opry broadcasts.{{sfn|Homer|2019|p=42}} She also recalled attending outdoor performances venues where country was played, notably Pennsylvania's Hillbilly Park. "I was always on the ground right in front of the
front row, looking up at the stage," she recalled in her website's biography.{{sfn|Seely|Harman|2002|p=1}} Seely also kept photographs of country performers she was inspired by, including [[Little Jimmy Dickens]] and [[Jean Shepard]].{{sfn|Seely|Harman|2002|p=2}} She also credited [[Ernest Tubb]], along with pop singers [[Rosemary Clooney]] and [[Patti Page]] as influences on her music.{{sfn|Homer|2019|p=41}}

==Legacy==
{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Jeannie Seely}}
Seely has been described as an influential female country artist. According to authors Mary Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann, Seely's stage presence and personality was unlike that of her predecessors. "When she arrived in Nashville in 1965, women were still expected to portray the submissive country sweetheart. Jeannie blazed a nonconformist trail from the moment she hit the Opry stage in her mini skirt."{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} Carrie Horton of ''The Boot'' called her career "prolific" and "influential". "From her success as a songwriter to her popularity as a duet partner to her influence as a solo artist, Seely's work has impacted generations of country, Americana and bluegrass performers," Horton commented.<ref name="Top 5"/> Edward Morris of ''[[Country Music Television]]'' called her "one of the Opry's most applauded performers."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Morris |first1=Edward |title=Women's History Month: These Artists Thrived in the '50s and '60s |url=http://www.cmt.com/news/1818877/womens-history-month-these-artists-thrived-in-the-50s-and-60s/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200630134154/http://www.cmt.com/news/1818877/womens-history-month-these-artists-thrived-in-the-50s-and-60s/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 30, 2020 |website=[[Country Music Television]] |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>

[[File:Jeannie Performing at ROPE.jpg|thumb|left|140px|Seely onstage at R.O.P.E. awards, 2010s]]
On the Grand Ole Opry, she became the first artist to wear a [[miniskirt]] on stage.<ref name="PBS"/> Seely challenged Opry manager Ott Devine, who disliked the idea of her wearing a miniskirt onstage. "Okay, this is what America is wearing and Iâ€™ll make you a deal. I wonâ€™t wear a miniskirt in the back door if you donâ€™t let anybody wear one in the front door," she recounted in Ken Burnsâ€™ ''[[Country Music (miniseries)|Country Music]]'' documentary.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Burns |first1=Ken |title=''Country Music'' (The Sons and Daughters of America) |journal=[[PBS]] |date=September 2019}}</ref> Seely was also among the first female artists to wear other contemporary fashion items, including [[go-go boot]]s, [[pantsuit]]s and [[jeans|denim jeans]]. Prior to Seely, many female country performers entertained in [[gingham]] and wore dresses on stage. According to Mary Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann, Seely "broke the Opry's gingham curtain". Seely later reflected on her choice of stage attire. "I never planned to set any sort of trend. I'm about like any other normal American girl my age. I think I dress and act pretty much the way she does," she recalled.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=302}}

Her music has also been an influence on other female country artists. Lorrie Morgan has considered Seely to be influence on her music. In a 2017 interview, Morgan called her "a great lady and a very good friend of mine."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Morgan |first1=Kim Kyle |title=Six questions with country music star Lorrie Morgan: Concert this Friday in The Woodlands |url=https://www.woodlandsonline.com/npps/story.cfm?nppage=59351 |website=Woodlands Online |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> [[Barbara Mandrell]] has also cited her as an influence.{{sfn|Homer, Sheree|2019|p=40}} [[Carly Pearce]] is a third female artist that has sought inspiration from Seely. "I dreamt of singing in the Grand Ole Opry my whole life. They are so dear to me, and I hope to be a member one day. Be like Jeannie â€“ she's kind of my inspiration as far as the Opry goes," Pearce commented.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Gayle |title=Carly Pearce Shares Most Treasured Possession on Display at the Country Music Hall of Fame |url=https://popculture.com/country-music/news/carly-pearce-treasured-possession-display-hall-of-fame/ |website=[[CBS Interactive|PopCulture.com]] |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>

In recent years, Seely has received honors for her accomplishments as a recording artist and writer. Her hometown of Townville, Pennsylvania has made her a "Grand Marshall" of their community parades on several occasions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Titusville, Pa Welcomes Grand Ole Opry Member, Jeannie Seely, As Featured Guest At 50th Townville Old Home Days |url=https://www.newcountrybuzz.com/2019/07/23/titusville-pa-welcomes-grand-ole-opry-member-jeannie-seely-as-featured-guest-at-50th-townville-old-home-days/ |website=Country Buzz |access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref> In 2017, Seely celebrated 50 years as a member of the Grand Ole Opry. She was among several women who have since been a member for 50 years. Among those have been [[Loretta Lynn]] and [[Dolly Parton]]. "The Opry has been my life for more than 50 years. I feel so blessed to be a part of this Opry family. Tonight was just the icing on the cake," she commented in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Papadaytos |first1=Markos |title=Review: Jeannie Seely makes 50-year history with Grand Ole Opry |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/music/review-jeannie-seely-makes-50-year-history-with-the-grand-ole-opry/article/502658 |website=Digital Journal |date=17 September 2017 |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> The same year, Seely was recognized for her life's work at 7th annual "NATD Honors Gala", along with [[Charley Pride]].<ref>{{cite web |title=7th Annual NATD Honors Gala Recognizes Charley Pride, Jeannie Seely, David Corlew, Barbara Hubbard, Sean Henry and Bobby Roberts |url=https://www.thecountrynote.com/in-the-news/7th-annual-natd-honors-gala-recognizes-charley-pride-jeannie-seely-david-corlew-barbara-hubbard-sean-henry-bobby-roberts/ |website=The Country Note |date=16 November 2017 |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>

In 2018, Seely received a star on the [[Music City Walk of Fame]].<ref name="Music City">{{cite web |author=GGM Staff |title=MISS COUNTRY SOUL," JEANNIE SEELY, HONORED WITH STAR ON MUSIC CITY WALK OF FAME |url=https://guitargirlmag.com/news/music-news/miss-country-soul-jeannie-seely-honored-with-star-on-music-city-walk-of-fame/ |website=Guitar Girl Magazine |date=23 August 2018 |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> Also in 2018, she received an award from ''Billboard'' magazine for the composition, "Anyone Who Know What Love Is (Will Understand)". The song reached number 2 on the "Top TV Songs" chart after its appearance in the show ''[[Black Mirror]]''.<ref name="Anyone"/> She was featured in [[Ken Burns]]'s documentary ''[[Country Music (miniseries)|Country Music]]'' in September 2019. Seely's music and career was profiled and she was also interviewed for several segments.<ref name="PBS"/> In late 2019, she received an [[honorary degree]] from [[Lincoln Memorial University]] in Tennessee. "This is an honor that exceeds even my dreams. I could never have imagined this. I hope that I can always be deserving of this title in all that I do," she commented in her acceptance speech.<ref name="LMU">{{cite web |author=Staff Reports |title=Lincoln Memorial University honors Seely with honorary doctorate |url=https://www.mainstreet-nashville.com/news/lincoln-memorial-university-honors-seely-with-honorary-doctorate/article_5efa983e-219f-11ea-8daf-2bba58dbc41f.html |website=Main Street Nashville |date=18 December 2019 |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> Between March 2019 and February 2020, artifacts from Seely's life and career were on display at the [[Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum]]. Titled, "American Currents", her life and career was beside the work of newer Nashville artists, most notably Carly Pearce.<ref>{{cite web |title=Grand Ole Opry Member, Jeannie Seely, Included in American Currents: The Music of 2018 at The Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Grand-Ole-Opry-Member-Jeannie-Seely-Included-in-American-Currents-The-Music-of-2018-at-The-Country-Music-Hall-of-Fame-and-Museum-20190117 |website=[[BroadwayWorld]] |access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref>

